The director, National Institute for Cultural Orientation, NICO, Mrs Bridgette Yerima, has emphasised the need to revisit and review  Nigeria’s Cultural Policy, 32 years after it was put in place. She lamented that Nigeria’s cultural policy, formulated in 1988 had become obsolete and needed to be reappraised, rejigged and updated, to tackle emerging social issues, including rape, child-molestation and domestic violence. In her words: “Countries like India, China, North Korea and Saudi Arabia have instituted punishment options of death, castration, beheading and death by firing squad. “Nigeria may need to move in that direction to curb the rising incidence of these rape cases.” Yerima, who is the director overseeing the office of executive secretary of NICO, argued that no punishment should be considered too harsh in protecting minors and old women, who have been at the receiving end of rapists in recent years. “There is no doubt that the rising cases of rape, child molestation and domestic violence in Nigeria are causing many citizens sleepless nights. This calls for creative solutions to stem the ugly tide,” she said.